sentences: Walter Andrew Brennan (July 25, 1894 – September 21, 1974) was an American actor and singer.

Brennan was given another lead role in God Is My Partner (1957), a low budget movie that was a surprise hit.
It was a hit and ran from 1957 to 1963.
Brennan continued to appear in films and other TV shows during the series' run such as Colgate Theatre and another Howard Hawks' picture, Rio Bravo (1959), in support to John Wayne and Dean Martin.
After five years on ABC, The Real McCoys switched to CBS for a final season.
For Brennan Productions, Brennan starred in Shoot Out at Big Sag (1962).
He appeared as a villainous river pirate up against James Stewart in MGM's epic How the West Was Won (1963).

Brennan's success with The Real McCoys led to him making a few recordings, the most popular being "Old Rivers", about an old farmer and his mule, which was released as a single in 1962 by Liberty Records with "The Epic Ride of John H. Glenn" on the flip side.
At age 68, Brennan reached the Top 40 again, this time with "Mama Sang a Song" on November 17, 1962.
Walter Brennan was among hundreds of artists whose material was destroyed in the 2008 Universal fire.
Brennan starred as the wealthy executive Walter Andrews in the short-lived 1964–1965 ABC series The Tycoon, with Van Williams.

In 1920, Brennan married Ruth Caroline Wells (1897-1997).
In 1920, Brennan married Ruth Caroline Wells (1897-1997).
They had three children in their 54 year marriage: Arthur, Walter, and Ruth.
In 1940, Brennan purchased the 12,000-acre Lightning Creek Ranch, 20 miles north of Joseph, Oregon.
In 1964, Brennan spoke at "Project Prayer", a rally attended by 2,500 at the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles.

The gathering, hosted by Anthony Eisley, sought to flood Congress with letters in support of mandatory school prayer, following two decisions of the Supreme Court in 1962 and 1963 that had struck down the practice of mandatory prayer in public schools as being in conflict with the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment to the United States Constitution.
Brennan spent his last years mostly in retirement at his ranch in Moorpark in Ventura County, California.
However, he remained somewhat embarrassed as to how he won the awards; in the early years of the Academy Awards, extras were given the right to vote.
Following this change, Brennan lost his fourth Best Supporting Actor nomination in 1941 for Sergeant York (the award went to Donald Crisp for How Green Was My Valley).
In all, Brennan appeared in more than 230 film and television roles during a career that spanned nearly five decades.
In 1970, he was inducted into the Western Performers Hall of Fame at the National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum in Oklahoma City, where his photograph hangs prominently.
